03959nam a22005055i 9780226067001DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260670017 a10.7208/97802260670012doi  a(DE-B1597)535565  a(OCoLC)721927640  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPN1994 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.431 aBordwell, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMinding Movies :bObservations on the Art, Craft, and Business of Filmmaking /cDavid Bordwell, Kristin Thompson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b75 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart One. The Business -- tPart Two. Writing about Movies -- tPart Three. Film as Art -- tPart Four. Storytelling and Style -- tPart Five. Films -- tPart Six. Into the Future -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDavid Bordwell and Kristin Thompson are two of America’s preeminent film scholars. You would be hard pressed to find a serious student of the cinema who hasn’t spent at least a few hours huddled with their seminal introduction to the field—Film Art, now in its ninth edition—or a cable television junkie unaware that the Independent Film Channel sagely christened them the “Critics of the Naughts.” Since launching their blog Observations on Film Art in 2006, the two have added web virtuosos to their growing list of accolades, pitching unconventional long-form pieces engaged with film artistry that have helped to redefine cinematic storytelling for a new age and audience. Minding Movies presents a selection from over three hundred essays on genre movies, art films, animation, and the business of Hollywood that have graced Bordwell and Thompson’s blog. Informal pieces, conversational in tone but grounded in three decades of authoritative research, the essays gathered here range from in-depth analyses of individual films such as Slumdog Millionaire and Inglourious Basterds to adjustments of Hollywood media claims and forays into cinematic humor. For Bordwell and Thompson, the most fruitful place to begin is how movies are made, how they work, and how they work on us. Written for film lovers, these essays—on topics ranging from Borat to blockbusters and back again—will delight current fans and gain new enthusiasts. Serious but not solemn, vibrantly informative without condescension, and above all illuminating reading, Minding Movies offers ideas sure to set film lovers thinking—and keep them returning to the silver screen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMotion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aThompson, Kristin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226067001423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226067001.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles